cs.LG, cs.SY, cs.IT, cs.NA, cs.DS

The paper deals with system identification, which is a problem in control theory and signal processing. The use of sparsity-promoting regularization techniques is a common approach in machine learning and signal processing, which suggests that the paper may belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category. The paper also deals with the properties of the estimator under high-dimensional scaling, which suggests that it may belong to the cs.SY (Systems and Control) sub-category. The paper also uses results from high-dimensional statistics, which suggests that it may belong to the cs.IT (Information Theory) sub-category. The paper also deals with the number of sample trajectories required for sparse system identification, which suggests that it may belong to the cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) sub-category. Finally, the paper offers case studies on synthetically generated systems, physical mass-spring networks, and multi-agent systems, which suggests that it may belong to the cs.DS (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) sub-category.
